    scripture: "And the world passeth away, and the lust thereof: but he that doeth the will of God abideth for ever.",
    walk: `Friend, as we near the end of our journey, John gives us a powerful motive for doing God's will: that while the world passes away, the one who does the will of God abides forever: *the world passeth away, and the lust thereof: but he that doeth the will of God abideth for ever.* The one who does God's will abides forever, while the world passes away. This teaches us, friend, that doing God's will has eternal significance; while the world and its desires pass away, the one who does the will of God abides forever.

Consider the passing of the world: *the world passeth away, and the lust thereof.* The world and its desires pass away. John reminds us, friend, that the world is passing away, and the lust thereof, the desires of the world. The world and all its desires, friend, all that it offers and promises, are passing away, temporary, fading. Nothing in the world lasts, friend; it is all passing away, here for a time and then gone. The things the world values, friend, the things it pursues, the desires it stirs up, are all passing away, temporary, with no lasting permanence. This is the nature of the world, friend, that it passes away.

And see the contrast: *but he that doeth the will of God abideth for ever.* The one who does God's will abides forever. In contrast to the passing world, friend, the one who does the will of God abides forever. While the world and its desires pass away, friend, the one who does God's will abides, lasts, endures forever. This is a powerful contrast, friend, between the passing world and the abiding permanence of the one who does God's will. The one who gives himself to the passing world, friend, passes away with it; but the one who does the will of God abides forever, enduring eternally. Doing God's will, friend, has eternal significance, connecting us to what is eternal and abiding.

What a motive this gives us for doing God's will, friend! While the world and all its desires are passing away, temporary and fading, the one who does the will of God abides forever. If we give ourselves to the passing world, friend, to its desires and pursuits, we give ourselves to what is passing away, and pass away with it. But if we give ourselves to doing God's will, friend, we give ourselves to what is eternal, and abide forever. Doing God's will, friend, is not a passing thing, but has eternal significance, connecting us to the eternal and abiding. This is a powerful motive, friend, to do God's will rather than to give ourselves to the passing world.

So give yourself to doing God's will, friend, knowing it has eternal significance, that while the world passes away, the one who does the will of God abides forever. Do not give yourself to the passing world, friend, to its desires and pursuits, all of which are passing away, temporary and fading; for if you give yourself to the passing world, you pass away with it. Rather, give yourself to doing God's will, friend, which has eternal significance, connecting you to what is eternal and abiding. For while the world and its desires pass away, friend, the one who does the will of God abides forever, enduring eternally. So let this be a powerful motive for you, friend, to do God's will rather than to give yourself to the passing world; for the world passes away, but the one who does God's will abides forever. So give yourself to doing God's will, friend, and abide forever, rather than giving yourself to the passing world and passing away with it. For he that doeth the will of God abideth forever. So do God's will, friend, and abide forever, connected to the eternal and abiding through doing the will of God.`,
    prayer: `Lord, thank You for this powerful motive for doing Your will, that while the world passes away, the one who does Your will abides forever. Help me to remember that the world and all its desires are passing away, temporary and fading, that nothing in the world lasts. And help me not to give myself to the passing world, to its desires and pursuits; for if I give myself to the passing world, I pass away with it. Rather, help me to give myself to doing Your will, which has eternal significance, connecting me to what is eternal and abiding. For while the world and its desires pass away, the one who does Your will abides forever. So let this be a powerful motive for me, to do Your will rather than to give myself to the passing world. Help me to do Your will and abide forever. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, give yourself to doing God's will, knowing it has eternal significance. Rather than giving yourself to the passing world and its desires, do the will of God, remembering that "he that doeth the will of God abideth for ever."`,
    reflect: `How does the contrast between the world that "passeth away" and the one who "abideth for ever" motivate you to do God's will? In what ways might you be giving yourself to the passing world and its desires, rather than to the eternal significance of doing God's will?`,
